  "topic_name": "Electricity and Magnetism",
  "canonical_explanation": {
    "text": "Electric current is the flow of electricity through conductors. A simple electric circuit needs: cell/battery (source), wire (path), bulb (device), and switch (controller). A closed circuit allows current to flow; an open circuit does not. Electrical conductors (metals, water) allow electricity to flow; insulators (rubber, plastic, wood) do not. Magnets are made of natural (lodestone) or artificial materials. Magnets have two poles (North and South), attract iron/nickel/cobalt, and have directive property. Like poles repel, unlike poles attract. Electromagnets are made by coiling wire around iron and passing current; they can be switched on and off.",
    "rules": [
      "Electric current: flow of electricity",
      "Circuit components: cell, wire, bulb, switch",
      "Closed circuit: complete path, current flows",
      "Open circuit: broken path, no current",
      "Conductors: allow electricity (metals, water)",
      "Insulators: block electricity (rubber, plastic, wood)",
      "Magnets have North and South poles",
      "Like poles repel, unlike poles attract",
      "Magnets attract iron, nickel, cobalt",
      "Electromagnet: magnet made using electricity",
      "Electromagnets can be switched on/off"
    ]
  },
